nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Well, that was a good slam, and can be made if planned better. But, first let us discuss the auction which was very good. The 2@D bid  was 4th suit forcing. That says "partner, I want to establish a game forcing auction, and keep the bidding lower." The next bids 3@H, is saying, "partner I am interested in a heart slam."  Npw, even though I only ostensbily have 11 HCP, I have a really good hand. |
PG| ***** 66 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I have two really good suits, and 2 singletons. I am also very interested in slam. So, my next bid is a control bid showing first or 2nd round control in clubs. Normally, you don't skip any suits in which you have controls. With my hand, I could bid 3@S, since I do have 2nd round control of spades. However, I decided that my singleton might not be of interest to roberta since she bid spades. Thus, I decided to just show my club control, and skip my spade control. Once roberta sees I have a club control, since she controls both diamonds and spades, it is just now a matter of how many key cards we have.|
PG| ***** 67 ***** |


nt||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So blackwood is fine, and since we are missing only one key card, six hearts is the correct contract. This is the sort of auction we will be discussing in great detail in my upcoming lessons on slam bidding.|
