^C@2nome: As added emphasis on Howard's teaching I have decided each week to collect many of his important @E@3instructions in one page under "Howard's Pearls"  which we can go over them many times. The following are my picks. I am sure you can find many more.

|FP|2|cp|8|at|
^C@2** |FP||cp||at|It is rarely right to play in 5 of a minor rather than 3N.
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|Over 2@C, you should almost always bid 2@D, unless you have a 5+ card suit with 2 of the top 3 honors.
|FP|2|cp|8|at| 
** |FP||cp||at|In general, you should avoid leading the opponents suits on opening lead (except sometimes trumps are a good lead.)
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|Always count your winners and losers before playing out the hand.  
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|Redouble shows 10+ points, and denies 4 card  support. 
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|In general, if partner opens 1 of a major and you have 4 card support, it is best to show it right away.
|FP|2|cp|8|at|
** |FP||cp||at|If you play Bergen Raises;
-- a simple raise to 2 is done with exactly 3 card support. If you have 4 card support, depending on your point count you must choose between 
-- jumping to 3 of the major, 
-- 3@D 7-10 points
-- 3@C 10-12 points or (3@D and 3@C are Reverse Bergen for the point ranges)
-- 2N and Splinter 12+ points. 
The only question is, how weak can the jump to 3 of a major be? I teach that it is 5-6, and opener is allowed to bid game with 18+. 

